author: @GlennMascarenhas
text: I've run into problems with Anaconda on windows 10 so I don't think I'd recommend that route. I think Anaconda messes with environment variables for some reason and it also still runs python 3.7 rather than python 3.8. Besides for some reason you have to run Anaconda Navigator as administrator on windows 10 in order to avoid a kernel error while using jupyter notebook, which kinda feels like newly installing the Navigator every time I need to run it. For now, Anaconda doesn't even start on my pc, gives some kind of FatalError (probably because I switched to python 3.8 to use with Pycharm), so I uninstalled it, then installed Jupyter notebook through regular pip install and honestly I find this is a way better, easier and faster method. Takes about 1/3rd the time to start a notebook as compared to Anaconda

author: @dotinsideacircle
text: Pretty good tutorial. Recommendations (even for noobies): Different Python versions should not be installed in the same location. MacOS default Python2 is located at /usr/bin. And when Python3 is installed via Homebrew it should be installed at /usr/local/bin. Virtual environments¬†should also be used because then Python3 or Python2 packages along with Jupyter can be installed in separate project folders. This way all projects will have their own dependencies, packages and files with zero conflicts. If you decide to change machines or take a project folder to some lab or something else everything just works. As an added bonus, when virtual environments are used Jupyter will automatically be using the correct kernel. e.g. If Jupyter is opened in a Python3 project folder the Jupyter 'New' menu will say Python3 by default. If Jupyter is opened in a Python2 project folder the Jupyter 'New' menu will say Python2 by default.
